<paragraph id="8C4BEE03892F9A72FF25F658FAE7FF54" blockId="3.[115,770,1388,2000]" lastBlockId="3.[807,1461,187,242]" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">
I found several sheets filed as 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FE47F658FD8BFA22" authorityName="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri." authorityYear="1800" box="[498,628,1388,1412]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leprosum">
<emphasis id="BE803211892F9A72FE47F658FD8BFA22" box="[498,628,1388,1412]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">S. leprosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in MA (MA 334600, MA 334584, MA 3334600/2, MA 334600/3); of these only MA 334600 (the 3 sheets) are potential neotype material, as MA 334584 does not match the protologue in being from Mexico (“Nee iter, Nueva Espana”) and being non-prickly version (prickles are mentioned in the protologue). The three sheets of MA 334600 are probably from the same plant; their morphology is all very similar. All are labelled as 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FD32F570FF3EF9DA" authority="Ortega" authorityName="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri." authorityYear="1800" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leprosum">
<emphasis id="BE803211892F9A72FD32F570FCFEF9FB" box="[647,769,1605,1629]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">S. leprosum</emphasis>
Ortega
</taxonomicName>
; MA 334600/2 with “ 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FE1FF551FEC6F93D" authority="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri. 1800" authorityName="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri." authorityYear="1800" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leprosum">Solanum leprosum Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri. 1800</taxonomicName>
” in the hand of José Demetrio Rodriguez, MA 334600/3 as “ 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FE83F594FDA6F91C" authority="Ortega" authorityName="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri." authorityYear="1800" box="[310,601,1697,1722]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leprosum">Solanum leprosum Ortega</taxonomicName>
decade/” in an unknown hand, and MA 334600 as “ 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FE41F5F5FF71F951" authority="Ortega" authorityName="Ortega, Ex. Hort. Matri." authorityYear="1800" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="leprosum">Solanum leprosum Ortega</taxonomicName>
” in what is probably the hand of Rodriguez, but without a date. MA 334600 is the best preserved sheet and has a bud and two flowers clearly showing the declinate style mentioned in the protologue and is chosen here as the neotype (
<figureCitation id="14CFF286892F9A72FD1DF409FD0CF8F2" box="[680,755,1852,1876]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[130,162,1926,1945]" captionTargetBox="[253,1353,185,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-78@2.[253,1353,185,1906]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. a, neotype of Solanum cymosum Ortega (=Solanum lanceolatum Cav.) (MA 476353); b, neotype of Solanum ficifolium Ortega (= Solanum ferrugineum Jacq.) (MA 334586); c, neotype of Solanum leprosum Ortega (=Solanum elaeagnifolium Cav.) (MA 334600); d, neotype of Solanum subbiflorum Ortega (=Solanum capense L.) (MA308482)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6327660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6327660/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">Fig. 1c</figureCitation>
). All of these specimens are clearly identifiable as 
<taxonomicName id="4BF49580892F9A72FD3CF46EFF47F834" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="elaeagnifolium">
<emphasis id="BE803211892F9A72FD3CF46EFF47F834" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="59">S. elaeagnifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described by Cavanilles five years earlier, also from material collected in Chile by Luis Née, the botanist on the Malaspina Expedition (1789-1794; 
<bibRefCitation id="E86593F2892F9A72FE5EF48DFD06F876" author="Munoz Garmendia, F." box="[491,761,1976,2000]" journalOrPublisher="Ministerio de Defensa, Madrid" pageId="3" pageNumber="59" refId="ref5078" refString="Munoz Garmendia, F. 1992. La expedicion Malaspina 1789 - 1794. Tomo III. Diarios y trabajos botanicos de Luis Nee. Ministerio de Defensa, Madrid." title="La expedicion Malaspina 1789 - 1794. Tomo III. Diarios y trabajos botanicos de Luis Nee" type="book" year="1992">Muñoz Garmendia, 1992</bibRefCitation>
) that circumnavigated the globe and sent many novelties back to Spain for cultivation in the Jardín Botánico.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
